commit.message: updating to mask errors into reported value
adjusting return code for errors in continue mode

fixing bail-outs for non-root users in diag mode

for specific efforts, recovery of more data rather than less is helpful.
  adding the `-c` option will now cause `cramfsck` to log the error and
  then continue processing aiding in specific recovery scenarios.

fix a printf warning

Reported by @rweather.

undef any existing PAGE_SIZE

According to @rweather, PAGE_SIZE is set to 65536 in mingw's headers.
minor doc updates
Merge commit 'refs/pull/2/head' of https://github.com/npitre/cramfs-tools

work around gcc-8's -Wstringop-truncation

Our strncpy() usage was exactly what was intended i.e. the buffer has
a fixed length and the terminating NULL can be missing if no room
for it. But gcc-8 doesn't like it.
macos support

mkcramfs: add ability to create cross-endian images

This is accomplished by providing either -L (little-endian) or
-B (big endian). Without either -B or -L the host native endian is
used by default.

mkcramfs: abstract filesystem image stores with accessors

This will make cross-endian image creation easier, as well as making
the code much clearer.
fix new warnings with gcc 7.3.1
clarify kernel version that supports new features

cramfsck: restore intended verbose output ordering for symlinks

do_symlink() no longer performs block level verbose output by itself.
This is now performed in read_block(). However we need to execute
read_block() to get the actual symlink value for its own verbose display
which outputs corresponding blocks before the symlink info.

Restore the expected ordering by
calling read_block() once with verbosity turned off, and once again
just for the verbose display if needed.

add latest filesystem format changes to cramfsck

This allows for validating and extracting data from a filesystem that
uses direct and uncompressed blocks.

resync header file content with the kernel code

This adds the CRAMFS_BLK_DIRECT_PTR_SHIFT define.

some docs updates

Also change PAGE_CACHE_SIZE to PAGE_SIZE as there is no longer
any trace of the former in the kernel source tree.
Move magic info to a separate file

auto-XIP of ELF loadable segments

Currently supports no-MMU (-X) and MMU (-X -X). The only difference
at the moment is the block alignment since on no-MMU it is not required
to be page aligned.

To mitigate the large alignment requirement, the MMU case could leverage
the direct block pointer's ability to gather all XIPable blocks together
at the end of the image (TODO).

repurpose do_compress() and replace with write_blocks()

This allows for error checking on zlib in one place.
add .gitignore

implement the creation of more block types

This makes for 4 possibilities: either traditional or direct,
and in each case either compressed or uncompressed.

The direct compressed block has no real advantage over the traditional one
except for repositioning the block sequence. The likely scenario is a
sequence of direct non compressed blocks for XIP located out-of-line
with other such blocks so the needed page alignment is padded only once
for the whole image. If only a portion of a file is represented with
direct uncompressed blocks then one direct compressed block would be
needed to bring the stream back to the compressed block area, after
which standard compressed blocks may occur.

improve compression statistics reporting

Especially now that compression can be skipped when not beneficial,
knowing the actual overhead becomes interesting.

Some code/variable cleanups.

add the -x argument to allow pointer extensions

Currently only used to avoid compressing data blocks when
compressed data is larger than the original data.

While at it, set the super block flags only when needed.

new flags from the Linux code

This provides the ability to do mixed compressed/uncompressed file segments and block
alignment for XIP applications.
make -q squash uid/gid of the root directory too
fix a bunch of warnings

Add mkfs.jffs2 compatible device table support

This patch adds support for mkfs.jffs2 compatible
device table files. I have also included a sample
device table file (the one from the MTD cvs tree) as
well as a patch adding support for them to mkcramfs. I
also fixed a few bugs I found in the cramfs 1.1
release. It would be very nice to see this applied to
the upstream source tree and released. It makes it
easy to build full filesystems (including device nodes,
proper permissions, etc) without needing to be root,
and is therefore used by the buildsystems for a number
of projects.

Fix crash cramfsck at die()

The call to die() in uncompress_block() passes parameters in wrong order. This
makes vfprintf() crash.
